rows.text: Last known sauropod in North America until appearance of Alamosaurus
A "transitional form" between two other species of ceratopsians.
An early hadrosaur with no crest on its snout.
A large predator with a hump or sail on its back.
The last known sauropod from North America.
One of North America's smallest adult non-avian dinosaurs.
Fossil evidence suggests it may have hunted in packs.
Its remains were found in California, thought it may have lived closer to Mexico in life.
Fossils have also been found in Europe.
Intertwined with Gryposaurus and Kritosaurus throughout its history.
A hadrosaur with an unusually-shaped jaw.
Discovered during a radiological survey of the fossil site.
Known for its heavily armored back.
Probably synonymous with Allosaurus, see article
One of the few non-avian dinosaurs from the eastern side of North America.
A hadrosaur from Big Bend National Park in Texas, described in 2019.
A nomen nudum for 41 years before being officially described in 2018.
Named after the familiar character due to its small size.
Probably one of the largest dinosaurs.
Only juvenile fossils found so far
A hadrosaur known from several well-preserved "mummies"
Probably the most common sauropod of Late Jurassic times.
Official dinosaur of the District of Columbia. The intersection near where it was found is now nicknamed "Capitalsaurus Court".
Formerly congeneric with Camarasaurus, split due to its unusual proportions.
Shows a strange mix of primitive and advanced features.
The species name was named after the author of Jurassic Park.
Not to be confused with Kentrosaurus
Type genus of the Ceratopsia and the Ceratopsidae. Currently considered dubious.
A large predator with armor scutes along its back.
A ceratopsian known from multiple remains.
An oviraptorosaur originally known from assorted body parts.
Has the longest brow horns of any ceratopsian.
A populous, long-lived genus. Includes "Megapnosaurus" and "Syntarsus".
The genus the Coelurosauria was named after.
This name is preoccupied, but by what is unknown.
A hadrosaur with a crest that resembles half a dinner plate.
An early theropod with a short snout and "buck teeth".
Once an American species of Iguanodon.
Possibly the direct ancestor of T. rex
Its discovery suggests non-avian dinosaurs were warm-blooded, active creatures.
One of the oldest centrosaurine ceratopsid.
Shares its name with an alien race in the manga series Elfen Lied.
Despite its appearance in the film Jurassic Park, it didn't have frills and probably couldn't spit poison.
Confused with various other vertebrates throughout its history.
Named after paleontologist Edward Drinker Cope.
One of the fastest non-avian dinosaurs.
Best known from a painting by Charles Knight.
A recently-described tyrannosaur from New Mexico.
It may have had four toes on its hind legs (unlike other sauropods which only have three)
Recently found to be a dicraeosaurid.
Known for its double-pointed shoulder spikes.
A ceratopsian with a forward-curving horn on its nose.
One of the few non-avian dinosaurs from Appalachia.
Possibly the largest species of ceratopsian.
May be the same as Allosaurus.
A transitional form between carnivorous theropods and herbivorous therizinosaurs.
One of the smallest non-avian dinosaurs.
An ankylosaur with multiple shoulder spikes.
Possibly a juvenile of an already known species.
A predator named after Godzilla because of its size.
A hadrosaur that may have eaten crabs.
The first non-avian dinosaur found in North America.
Either a diplodocid or a macronarian.
A stegosaur that may have possessed sexual dimorphism.
One of the few known ornithopods from Mexico.
A hadrosaur that may have cared for its young.
Named after the Zuni for "grinding mouth".
A sauropod known for its "toothy smile".
A large theropod of the Early Jurassic.
Has the most horns of any ceratopsian.
A hadrosaur with a large bump on its nose.
An indeterminate theropod, possibly a tyrannosaur or a carcharodontosaurid.
A hadrosaur with a hollow, hatchet-shaped crest.
Possibly the same as another of the Morrison neornithischians.
Not to be confused with Altirhinus.
A basal ceratopsian that lived towards the end of the Mesozoic.
The first non-avian dinosaur found in Alabama.
A tyrannosaur with one tooth larger than the rest of its teeth.
Not to be confused with Megalodon.
Its fossils suggest hadrosaurs cared for their young.
Named after the snake-haired woman of Greek myth, which its horns are said to resemble.
Named after the winged messenger of the gods in Roman mythology.
First appeared as a nomen nudum in 2006 and only formally described in 2017.
A basal ceratopsian originally thought to have a horn on its snout.
May include Drinker, Othnielia and Othnielosaurus.
A small tyrannosaur from polar latitudes.
A ceratopsian known for its large nose and cow-like horns.
Includes "Diceratops". May be a Triceratops individual.
North America's most complete known therizinosaur.
May belong to either Triceratops or Eotriceratops.
Named after scientist Othniel Charles Marsh.
Most Othnielia remains have been transferred to this animal.
Has a dome on the top of its head.
Three species are known that have different head shapes.
A hadrosaur known for its large, long, tube-like crest.
Despite its name, it only has three horns.
Highly dubious; may be the same as Coelophysis.
Known from the imprints of a skeleton, not actual fossilized bones.
Similar-looking teeth have been found in South America, Europe, and Asia.
May be the same as Styracosaurus, and Brachyceratops may represent its juveniles.
Once thought to represent American specimens of Massospondylus.
A species is also found in Mongolia.
A nodosaur with a long tail.
Possibly the top land predator of the Late Jurassic
An ankylosaur with a convoluted taxonomic history.
A sauropodomorph whose holotype specimen may have died during the collapse of a sand dune.
The largest carnivorous dinosaur in North America before the appearance of T. rex.
Its holotype specimen was once said as being "nothing but rubbish".
Not to be confused with Stegosaurus.
Well-known for the plates and spikes on its back.
Most Troodon remains were transferred to this genus.
May be the same as Lambeosaurus.
Known for the spikes that surrounded its frill.
The first known North American dicraeosaurid.
Named for a bronze automaton in Greek mythology.
An iguanodont with a very long tail.
Unusual structures on its head have been compared to gears.
A skull of Camptosaurus has been referred to this genus.
One specimen was once thought to have preserved its heart.
It has one of the largest skulls of any known animal.
Once thought to have been an adult Triceratops.
Known for the three horns and the frill on its head.
Its discovery may have influenced the design of the Velociraptors in the Jurassic Park film series.
A tooth taxon that may represent a dromaeosaur.
Named after the Zia sun symbol on the flag of New Mexico.
One of the oldest ceratopsians with horns.
Named after Zuul from the film Ghostbusters.
